<name>Snowdonia — Conwy to Caernarfon via Llanberis Pass</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Snowdonia — Conwy to Caernarfon via Llanberis Pass</h2><p><i>Wales · Eryri (Snowdonia) National Park, Conwy to Caernarfon</i></p><p><b>Two Edward I castles bracketing a drive through the highest mountains in England and Wales.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>57 km (35 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>2–3 hrs</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>April–October (rains often regardless; bring waterproofs)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Rain (constant), low cloud, narrow stone-walled lanes, sheep, queueing for parking at Pen-y-Pass</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>108</td></tr></table><hr><p>Eryri (the older Welsh name, now official) is the highest land in Wales — Yr Wyddfa (Snowdon) at 1,085 m is the highest point in England and Wales. Conwy and Caernarfon, at the start and end of this drive, are two of the great Edwardian castles built by Edward I after his conquest of Wales in the 1280s — both UNESCO World Heritage. Between them, the road climbs through the Pass of Llanberis (Bwlch Llanberis), below the Glyderau and Yr Wyddfa, with the slate-quarry village of Llanberis at the foot of the mountain. Beddgelert is named for the dog Gelert (a medieval folktale; possibly invented by an 18th-century innkeeper to attract tourists — it worked).</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Conwy Castle</b> — 1283–87, UNESCO. Eight massive towers, almost completely intact. The walled town below is also fully intact — only walled town in Britain you can walk completely around at street level.</li><li><b>Betws-y-Coed / Swallow Falls</b> — Stone village in the Gwydir Forest. Swallow Falls (Rhaeadr Ewynnol) tumbles in three drops just above the village.</li><li><b>Pen-y-Pass</b> — 359 m. Trailhead for several routes up Yr Wyddfa, including the Pyg Track and Miners' Track. Parking fills by 8 AM in summer; there's a shuttle bus from Llanberis.</li><li><b>Llanberis</b> — Slate-quarry town at the foot of Yr Wyddfa. Snowdon Mountain Railway (1896) climbs the summit on a rack railway. National Slate Museum tells the story of the industry that built half of Britain's roofs.</li><li><b>Caernarfon Castle</b> — Edward I's most ambitious Welsh castle (begun 1283), modeled on the walls of Constantinople. UNESCO. Investiture site for Princes of Wales since 1911.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
